LP, vitiligo and psoriasis show "true" koebner phenomenon while molluscum contagiosum and verruca vulgaris (the infective ones) show pseudo-koebnerization. - Source
+ Mnemonic: pregnancy - one 1, post partum - 2ps, means worsens psoriasis
+ Most common ones are : beta blockers, lithium, antimalarial drugs, NSAIDS and tetracyclines. (also exacerbation) (Mnemonic: "BLAND - D for doxycycline")

  • Most often, self limited and does not require treatment.

REDMAN : Radiation, Eczema / psoriasis, Drugs, Malignancy (mycosis fungoides, CTCL, Autoimmune, No identifiable cause)

Aetiology unknown - may be caused by immune reaction to malassezia furfur, a commensal.

Stevens-Johnson syndrome and Toxic epidermal necrolysis both affect skin and mucous membranes.

  • SJS < 10% of body area
  • TEN > 30% of body surface area.
    Treatment: Supportive +/- immunosuppresive (IVIG, corticosteroids, plasmapheresis, cyclosporine)
    Source

Keratocanthoma

  • Rapidly growing, locally destructive skin tumour with central keratinous plug.
  • Occurs in people over 60, with fair skin.
  • Clinically indisginguishable from squamous cell carcinoma. Therefore, often called SCC KA-type. Source
    Actinic keratosis is a premalignant lesion which can transform into squamous cell carcinoma.
    Actinic = means due to sun light.

Tends to occurs in young adults or teen.
Cause unknown.
May be preceded by flu like symptoms.
Herald patch occurs first.
No other systemic effects, resolves spontaneously in about 6 weeks.
Treatment: General measures, steroid if itching is severe. Can be treated with acylovir due to putative viral aetiology.

  • In Kikuchi-Fujimoto disease,the most common histologic finding is lymph node showing geographic necrosis with foci of apoptotic cells with abundant karyorrhectic fragments surrounded by histiocytes. no neutrophils or eosinophils
  • Treat with terbinafine.
  • Superficial infection caused by corynebacterium minutissimum. (bacterial infection)
  • First line therapy is topical erythromycin (Mnemonic, erythrasma -> erythromycin) or clindamycin, but topical miconazole also works.
  • Treated with topical antibacterial, miconazole and if severe, oral erythromycin.
  • Pytiriasis is caused by malassezia species.
